With these W18O49NWs as EC materials, a highly flexible dual-responsive film is prepared using a spray-coating method (Illustrated in Supplementary Fig. 1e). In the active area, ultrathin poly(3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene)-poly(styrenesulfonate) (PEDOT:PSS) is coated onto the pure AgNW network to protect the AgNWs from electrochemical corrosion. W18O49NW networks stack on AgNW/PEDOT:PSS networks, which forms a bilayer nanowire network (BNN) on a polyethylene terephthalate (PET) substrate with a thickness of ca. 15 μm. Figure 1b, c exhibit the surface and cross-section morphologies of the as-prepared dual-responsive film. The thickness of the bilayer nanowire network is only ~195 nm, which is much thinner than almost all of the EC active layers reported in previous literature20–22. This ultra-thin active layer could efficiently improve the bendability and foldability according to following equation23,1Rmin=b21ΔL-1,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
